📝 Overview
Predicting treatment retention is critical for healthcare outcomes. This project builds a binary classification model to predict whether a patient undergoing treatment for Opioid Use Disorder (OUD) will end their episode in a DROPOUT. This helps providers identify high-risk individuals and potentially intervene early.

🧰 Tech Stack & Dependencies
Python 3.x: Core programming language.

Scikit-Learn: Used for creating flexible pipelines, hyperparameter tuning via GridSearchCV, and model evaluation.

XGBoost: A gradient-boosted decision tree algorithm used to achieve high predictive accuracy.

TensorFlow/Keras: For exploring deep learning performance on patient data.

Matplotlib: For visualizing feature importance and subgroup performance disparities.

🛠️ Installation & Setup
Clone the repository:

Bash
git clone [your-repo-url]
cd [your-repo-folder]
Install dependencies:

Bash
pip install pandas numpy matplotlib scikit-learn xgboost tensorflow
🚀 Usage
Run the script:

Bash
python MIS548_Project_Problem2_OUD.py
Results: The script runs a comparative analysis between the Logistic Regression baseline, a tuned XGBoost model, and a Neural Network, outputting the best-performing model's results.

Subgroup Analysis: Review the printed tables to check model performance across demographic subgroups (e.g., Age, Race, Gender).

🧠 How It Works
Tuning: Employs GridSearchCV to optimize the XGBoost model by iterating through parameters like max_depth and learning_rate.

Feature Engineering: One-hot encoding and imputation are applied to handle heterogeneous patient data types.

Fairness Check: Includes a specific subgroup_auc_table function to verify that the model performs consistently across different patient populations, ensuring equitable predictive power.
